 <p><small> - Kalelce</small></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukivrinmillefleurs.showPublicProfile?language=EN>KivrinMillefleurs</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/10/02 2:55:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2024.topic&index=90>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Where did your name come from?</span><hr size=1> I have to admit, I shamelessly took the name Kivrin from The Doomsday Book by Connie Willis. It's one of my favorite fantasy novels and the name stuck in my head long after I had finished reading it.<br>
<br>
I had a harder time figuring out a surname. I wanted something that would relate to who Kivrin was (a woodelf druid) as well as a name that was meaningful to me in some way. I've always been interested in art history and fascinated with medieval tapestries. One day I was flipping through a book describing The Lady and the Unicorn tapestries in the Cluny Museum in France when it hit me. Because of the thousands of flowers woven into the background of each panel, art historians refer to them as mille-fleurs (&quot;a thousand flowers&quot;) tapestries. What better name for a nature-loving druid? <br>
<br>
Incidentally, I've started working on Kivrin's background, and her name will have more meaning as she gets older (I didn't realize until recently, for example, that she will need to speak to a pained unicorn in LFay as part of her epic quest).<br>
<br>
Of course, once she gets married to Jorrick, her name will change to Aylwin...<br>
